WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.580
 - So hello, welcome to chapter six.

00:00:02.580 --> 00:00:06.740
 In this chapter we talk about structures, but so much more.

00:00:06.740 --> 00:00:12.220
 There is a mid-chapter surprise in this book,

00:00:12.220 --> 00:00:15.940
 and I am sure that it's so surprising that it's caused

00:00:15.940 --> 00:00:20.100
 a few too many people to drop out of computer science,

00:00:20.100 --> 00:00:23.520
 first computer science course.

00:00:23.520 --> 00:00:27.520
 And that's because in sections 6.1 through 6.4,

00:00:29.080 --> 00:00:31.960
 we're learning the C language.

00:00:31.960 --> 00:00:34.480
 And we're learning just what a structure is.

00:00:34.480 --> 00:00:37.560
 It's a simple, beautiful, elegant concept.

00:00:37.560 --> 00:00:39.900
 It's sort of a wrapper for a whole bunch of types.

00:00:39.900 --> 00:00:42.920
 It groups them together so that you can create a new type.

00:00:42.920 --> 00:00:45.820
 And it really at this point is the last foundational

00:00:45.820 --> 00:00:50.400
 component of the core C languages, core C language.

00:00:50.400 --> 00:00:53.980
 And then in section 6.5, the authors pivot

00:00:57.660 --> 00:01:00.000
 to talking about data structures.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:04.700
 And that is the applications of C structures.

00:01:04.700 --> 00:01:08.240
 And it's the foundational notion in computer science.

00:01:08.240 --> 00:01:10.140
 It's the kind of thing where how do you build

00:01:10.140 --> 00:01:12.220
 a Python dictionary in C.

00:01:12.220 --> 00:01:18.200
 And so this is a pattern we call the knee of the curve,

00:01:18.200 --> 00:01:22.040
 where things are going along just fine up to 6.4.

00:01:22.040 --> 00:01:25.500
 Like, oh, here's a for loop, and here's a string,

00:01:25.500 --> 00:01:27.640
 and here's an array.

00:01:27.640 --> 00:01:29.660
 And here's even a pointer that's not that hard.

00:01:29.660 --> 00:01:31.140
 And structures are not that hard.

00:01:31.140 --> 00:01:34.680
 But then when we start talking about applications

00:01:34.680 --> 00:01:37.880
 of structures, what we call data structures.

00:01:37.880 --> 00:01:41.280
 Structures was named because data structures was a concept.

00:01:41.280 --> 00:01:45.780
 But how we use structures is a next level thing.

00:01:45.780 --> 00:01:47.860
 We're kind of leveling up.

00:01:47.860 --> 00:01:51.740
 So I want you, starting from here,

00:01:51.740 --> 00:01:55.620
 chapter six is the last real chapter that I'm gonna cover.

00:01:55.620 --> 00:01:59.260
 But it is expanding, 'cause chapter six is the beginning

00:01:59.260 --> 00:02:03.420
 of a whole additional course, a course on data structures.

00:02:03.420 --> 00:02:09.040
 So I want you, if you're rushing, I want you to slow down.

00:02:09.040 --> 00:02:12.580
 I want you to take your time and understand.

00:02:12.580 --> 00:02:17.140
 Because if you understand this, you can literally,

00:02:17.140 --> 00:02:21.000
 you have a doorway into a lot of computer science.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:24.140
 We'll talk about recursion even by the end.

00:02:24.140 --> 00:02:26.140
 And so just don't rush.

00:02:26.140 --> 00:02:28.900
 Work on mastery.

00:02:28.900 --> 00:02:30.520
 These are complex concepts.

00:02:30.520 --> 00:02:33.520
 They are not natural to understand.

00:02:33.520 --> 00:02:38.740
 And so before we start, I wanna do something different.

00:02:38.740 --> 00:02:42.260
 I wanna read you a poem.

00:02:42.260 --> 00:02:45.820
 One of my favorite poems from Robert Frost.

00:02:45.820 --> 00:02:49.980
 I was lucky enough, fortunate enough to be a good friend

00:02:49.980 --> 00:02:53.540
 of Bob Frost, who was a grandson of Robert Frost.

00:02:53.540 --> 00:02:56.600
 Bob Frost had a connection to the University of Michigan.

00:02:56.600 --> 00:02:58.340
 Robert Frost has a Michigan

00:02:58.340 --> 00:03:01.380
 and University of Michigan connection.

00:03:01.380 --> 00:03:06.100
 And I loved this poem that I'm about to read you

00:03:06.100 --> 00:03:10.580
 long before I met Bob Frost, the grandson of Robert Frost.

00:03:10.580 --> 00:03:17.100
 So the poem that I talk a lot about,

00:03:17.100 --> 00:03:23.380
 and really it's one line, miles to go before I sleep.

00:03:24.300 --> 00:03:26.500
 This is the poem called Stopping by the Woods

00:03:26.500 --> 00:03:28.380
 on a Snowy Evening.

00:03:28.380 --> 00:03:31.960
 And to me, it speaks of the notion

00:03:31.960 --> 00:03:36.960
 that journeys are not short nor easy, and it's okay.

00:03:36.960 --> 00:03:40.420
 Except that.

00:03:40.420 --> 00:03:41.660
 So here we go.

00:03:41.660 --> 00:03:43.880
 Dr. Chuck in poetry.

00:03:43.880 --> 00:03:49.200
 Whose woods these are, I think I know.

00:03:49.200 --> 00:03:51.780
 His house is in the village though.

00:03:51.780 --> 00:03:54.580
 He will not see me stopping here to watch his woods

00:03:54.580 --> 00:03:56.540
 fill up with snow.

00:03:56.540 --> 00:03:58.900
 My little horse must think it queer

00:03:58.900 --> 00:04:01.260
 to stop without a farmhouse near,

00:04:01.260 --> 00:04:03.780
 between the woods and frozen lake,

00:04:03.780 --> 00:04:05.920
 the darkest evening of the year.

00:04:05.920 --> 00:04:09.660
 He gives his harness bells a shake

00:04:09.660 --> 00:04:12.820
 to ask if there is some mistake.

00:04:12.820 --> 00:04:15.060
 The only other sounds the sweep

00:04:15.060 --> 00:04:18.020
 of easy wind and downy flake.

00:04:18.020 --> 00:04:22.140
 The woods are lovely, dark, and deep,

00:04:22.140 --> 00:04:24.480
 but I have promises to keep,

00:04:24.480 --> 00:04:28.380
 and miles to go before I sleep,

00:04:28.380 --> 00:04:31.980
 and miles to go before I sleep.

00:04:31.980 --> 00:04:38.900
 So the essence of this is that you have come a long way

00:04:38.900 --> 00:04:44.500
 to get to 6.4 in this book,

00:04:44.500 --> 00:04:48.420
 and it may feel like you've gone long enough,

00:04:48.420 --> 00:04:52.300
 and you should just pat yourself on the back,

00:04:52.300 --> 00:04:56.740
 but after 6.4, there are miles to go before I sleep.

00:04:56.740 --> 00:05:00.780
 But the good news is, when you're done, you can relax.

00:05:00.780 --> 00:05:04.380
 So what I want you to do is take your time,

00:05:04.380 --> 00:05:08.820
 things get much more complex really fast going forward,

00:05:08.820 --> 00:05:11.260
 and I don't want to lose you.

00:05:14.660 --> 00:05:17.740
 (gentle piano music)

